    <!-- http://www.semanticweb.org/90958855/ontologies/2024/8/riesma_thesis#Panama_disease -->

    <owl:NamedIndividual rdf:about="http://www.semanticweb.org/90958855/ontologies/2024/8/riesma_thesis#Panama_disease">
        <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.semanticweb.org/90958855/ontologies/2024/8/riesma_thesis#fungi"/>
        <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.semanticweb.org/90958855/ontologies/2024/8/riesma_thesis#fungi_as_a_pest"/>
        <has_name>Fusarium wilt</has_name>
        <rdfs:comment>Panama Disease, also known as Fusarium wilt, is a lethal fungal disease that attacks banana plants. It is caused by the soil-borne fungus Fusarium oxysporum f. sp. cubense (Foc), and there are several strains of this pathogen, the most infamous of which is Tropical Race 4 (TR4).</rdfs:comment>
    </owl:NamedIndividual>
    


    <!-- http://www.semanticweb.org/90958855/ontologies/2024/8/riesma_thesis#Papaya_CUH-CP551-8 -->

    <owl:NamedIndividual rdf:about="http://www.semanticweb.org/90958855/ontologies/2024/8/riesma_thesis#Papaya_CUH-CP551-8">
        <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.semanticweb.org/90958855/ontologies/2024/8/riesma_thesis#crop_variety"/>
        <hasDesign rdf:resource="http://www.semanticweb.org/90958855/ontologies/2024/8/riesma_thesis#allow_plant_to_metabolise_antibiotic"/>
        <hasDesign rdf:resource="http://www.semanticweb.org/90958855/ontologies/2024/8/riesma_thesis#produce_blue_stain_on_tissue"/>
        <hasDesign rdf:resource="http://www.semanticweb.org/90958855/ontologies/2024/8/riesma_thesis#produce_coat_protein_of_the_PRSV"/>
        <hasSpecies rdf:resource="http://www.semanticweb.org/90958855/ontologies/2024/8/riesma_thesis#Escherichia_coli"/>
        <hasSpecies rdf:resource="http://www.semanticweb.org/90958855/ontologies/2024/8/riesma_thesis#papaya"/>
        <hasSpecies rdf:resource="http://www.semanticweb.org/90958855/ontologies/2024/8/riesma_thesis#papaya_ringspot_virus"/>
        <authorisation_country>Canada</authorisation_country>
        <authorisation_country>Japan</authorisation_country>
        <authorisation_country>United States</authorisation_country>
        <developed_by>Cornell University and University of Hawaii</developed_by>
        <has_name>Rainbow, SunUp</has_name>
        <resistance_to_antibiotic>kanamycin</resistance_to_antibiotic>
        <resistance_to_antibiotic>neomycin</resistance_to_antibiotic>
        <resistance_to_disease>Papaya ringspot virus disease</resistance_to_disease>
        <rdfs:comment>Papaya variety that has ability to produce coat protein that confers resistance to PRSV disease, to metabolise neomycin and kanamycin antibiotics, and produces blue stain on treated transformed tissue. The novel traits resulted from particle mediated transformation which introduced a DNA construct into papaya plant cells. The PRSV CP gene is derived from the papaya ringspot virus strain PRSV HA 5-1. The plant expression of the viral coat protein confers the ability to resist the PRSV. The GUS gene is derived from Escherichia coli and the NPTII gene was originally obtained from the Tn5 transposon.</rdfs:comment>
        <rdfs:comment>https://www.isaaa.org/gmapprovaldatabase/event/default.asp?EventID=227&amp;Event=55-1
https://www.fao.org/food/food-safety-quality/gm-foods-platform/browse-information-by/oecd-unique-identifier/oecd-unique-identifier-details/en/?ui=169522</rdfs:comment>
    </owl:NamedIndividual>
    


